@Ziona I think the graph also indicates the forty-plus group believes the world is getting better generation by generation. 
I don't understand what you mean "the survey did not include responses from other countries."
Great headline!

@lilly This is a great response, and I particularly like your wondering here: "We also wonder about what people are thinking when they answer this question. For example, do they think that the world will become more peaceful or will their singular life get better?"

This gets at the question of survey design. Do you think they could have made the survey question more specific? What would be the advantages of asking about peacefulness specifically? What would be the disadvantages of specifying the question in this way?

To read more about the questions asked in the survey, you may want to go to the UNICEF interactive site “The Changing Childhood.”  (UNICEF sponsored this international, intergenerational study.)  On the site, there is a link to the report that has lots of other findings and explains how the survey was executed.

@Cierra These are some great observations, and it's great how you noticed that younger people tend to have more optimism. 

This line of your response spurred some great thinking for me: "If the data is accurate that means it's good that the younger people are more optimistic because they are the leading generation."

One question about the above: Would the older generations (particularly in more pessimistic countries) agree with you that it's "good" that the younger generation is so optimistic? Why or why not? What do you think?

@Caroline AOSE Great comments! Thank you for sharing.

You point out Morocco, India, and Nigeria as countries where the older generation is particularly optimistic (compared to other countries). I'd add two more countries to that list, in which we can see more optimism from the older generation than Morocco. Can you figure out which two countries this is?

One great pattern you recognized was that these three countries are the only ones below the line on the graph. What does it mean that these countries are below the line?
